        "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
        "body": "Thanks for filing Payas - much easier to provide a detailed response here than on Twitter :)\r\n\r\nThere are several reasons why Terminal is classified as a \"full-trust\" app and thus, why its permissions described in the Store look so ... expansive:\r\n\r\n## 1: Terminal needs the ability to run elevated\r\n\r\nTools and scripts that need to be elevated with admin rights need to be connected to a Terminal/Console instance running at the same Integrity Level (IL) - High-IL in the case of elevated processes.\r\n\r\nCurrently, modern UWP managed/packaged applications cannot run elevated. We are working with the app platform team to support this requirement in a future OS release.\r\n\r\n## 2: Terminal needs the ability to launch arbitrary command-line binaries\r\n\r\nIn order for the Terminal to be useful, it needs to connect to and run arbitrary command-line binaries that _you_ want to run, like `Cmd.exe`, `PowerShell.exe`, `WSL.exe`, `ping.exe`, etc.\r\n\r\nUWP apps are not allowed to launch and connect to arbitrary binaries. Again, we are working with the app platform team to support this requirement in a future OS release.\r\n\r\n## 3: Terminal needs the ability to access files in arbitrary locations\r\n\r\nTerminal needs to be able to access files stored in locations you specify on your machine, some of which are currently unreachable by managed UWP apps.\r\n\r\n## So ...\r\n\r\nDue to these issues, it's clear why we had to build Terminal as a Win32 app for now. And thus, because the Terminal is a full-trust Win32 app (which don't offer/support granular activity-based permissions like modern apps do), the Store's permissions description is correspondingly expansive.\r\n\r\nOnce the app platform can support our requirements, and allow us to declare our specific needs (e.g. \"Run Elevated\" or \"Launch External Processes\"), we'll be able to publish the Terminal as a more restricted, and explicit modern UWP app.\r\n\r\nHowever, now that you can see the source code that implements both the Terminal, and the Console, you'll see that we do not access your camera, microphone, scan your files, etc.\r\n\r\nLet me know if you have any further questions.",
