        "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
        "body": "@PayasR Sure! I'll be brief, since it's late here, but here's the gist.\r\n\r\nOur application is a full-trust application masquerading as a UWP, masquerading as a full-trust application. There's a bunch of different layers here -- we built the core components of the Terminal as though we were building a universal application to run inside the sandbox, but, as Rich alluded to, the sandbox isn't quite the right fit for something that needs the ability to spawn other applications...\r\n\r\nWe've been pushing a dependency on the team who owns the application infrastructure to make sure that we don't need this \"full trust\" moniker. It's been an interesting discussion to have here on the inside, because an application that can spawn other applications that can administer the system is only a single shade _away_ from being a full trust application. Further, it's been _fun_ (and by fun I mean, broadly speaking, frustrating) to dig through the windows application security model in search of a way to do what we need to do. :smile:",
